<% content_for :title, "Crooz — The Unbundling" %>

<main class="flex flex-column min-block-size-dvh">
  <header class="pad-double txt-align-center">
    <p class="txt-small txt-petrol txt-uppercase txt-spaced margin-block-end-half">Crooz Club</p>
    <h1 class="txt-xx-large margin-block-end-half txt-balance">Unbundling the Pleasure of Cruising an Automobile</h1>
    <p class="txt-subtle txt-small">14 Feb, 2026</p>
  </header>

  <div class="border-top-dashed"></div>

  <article class="pad-double prose center max-width-prose">
    <p class="txt-medium">
      People say they love automobiles. But that&rsquo;s like saying you love music &mdash;
      it doesn&rsquo;t say anything. What exactly do you love? The answer is never one thing.
      It&rsquo;s a stack of pleasures, layered on top of each other, each one distinct,
      each one enough to hook you on its own.
    </p>

    <p>Here&rsquo;s the unbundling.</p>

    <h2>1. The Instinct</h2>
    <p>
      Before you search, before you even know what you want &mdash; something pulls you.
      A shape glimpsed in traffic. A sound at a red light. A photo you can&rsquo;t scroll past.
      You don&rsquo;t choose it. It chooses you.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some people are drawn to Italian curves. Others to German precision.
      Some to the raw, unfinished honesty of a British sports car that will absolutely break down on you.
      This isn&rsquo;t rational. It&rsquo;s taste, and taste is a compass.
    </p>

    <h2>2. The Hunt</h2>
    <p>
      Now you&rsquo;re looking. Classifieds, forums, that one guy on Leboncoin who
      &ldquo;knows what he has.&rdquo; You learn to read between the lines of an ad.
      &ldquo;Runs great&rdquo; means it runs. &ldquo;Patina&rdquo; means rust.
      &ldquo;Reluctant sale&rdquo; means the wife won.
    </p>
    <p>The hunt is its own drug. You&rsquo;re not just shopping &mdash; you&rsquo;re stalking.</p>

    <h2>3. The Bet</h2>
    <p>
      This is the collector&rsquo;s edge. You spot a model before the market does.
      An air-cooled 911 in 2010. A Lancia Delta Integrale before Instagram discovered it.
      A manual BMW when everyone&rsquo;s chasing automatics.
    </p>
    <p>
      You put money where your instinct is. If you&rsquo;re right, the automobile pays you back &mdash;
      in value, and in the quiet satisfaction of having seen it coming.
    </p>

    <h2>4. The Keys</h2>
    <p>
      The moment it&rsquo;s yours. You sign, you transfer, you hold the keys,
      and something shifts. It&rsquo;s not just an automobile anymore. It&rsquo;s <em>yours</em>.
      The first time you adjust the mirrors, the seat, the steering wheel &mdash;
      you&rsquo;re not customizing. You&rsquo;re nesting.
    </p>

    <h2>5. The Machine</h2>
    <p>
      Pop the hood. This is where engineering becomes art.
      A flat-six that sounds like nothing else.
      A twin-cam head designed by someone who clearly loved their job.
      The mechanical sympathy of a gearbox that slots into place like a rifle bolt.
    </p>
    <p>
      You don&rsquo;t need to be a mechanic to appreciate this.
      You just need to care that someone, somewhere, solved a hard problem beautifully.
    </p>

    <h2>6. The Spirit</h2>
    <p>
      Every great manufacturer has a soul. Porsche is obsessive iteration &mdash;
      the same idea, refined for sixty years. Alfa Romeo is passion that occasionally
      forgets to check the wiring. Lotus is the religion of lightness.
      Citro&euml;n is &ldquo;what if we just&hellip; ignored convention entirely?&rdquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      When you drive one, you&rsquo;re not just using a product.
      You&rsquo;re in dialogue with a philosophy.
    </p>

    <h2>7. The Drive</h2>
    <p>
      This is the obvious one, but it&rsquo;s not simple. It&rsquo;s the weight of the steering
      at low speed. The way the throttle responds &mdash; linear, progressive, or that turbo lag
      that makes you plan three seconds ahead. The brakes that bite or the brakes that breathe.
      The suspension that reads the road to you like braille.
    </p>
    <p>
      A great drive is a conversation between you and the road, mediated by the machine.
      Some automobiles translate faithfully. Others editorialize.
      The best ones make you a better driver than you are.
    </p>

    <h2>8. The Stage</h2>
    <p>
      Let&rsquo;s be honest. Part of it is being seen. The head-turns. The kid who points.
      The guy at the gas station who says &ldquo;nice ride&rdquo; and means it.
      The parking lot where you pick the spot with the best backdrop
      without admitting that&rsquo;s why you picked it.
    </p>
    <p>
      This isn&rsquo;t vanity. It&rsquo;s the pleasure of sharing something beautiful with the world,
      even if the world is just a random Tuesday afternoon.
    </p>

    <h2>9. The Ritual</h2>
    <p>
      Saturday afternoon. The bucket, the chamois, the slow circles on the hood.
      Checking the tire pressure even though you checked it last week.
      Wiping down the dashboard with a cloth that costs more than it should.
      Topping off fluids that don&rsquo;t need topping off.
    </p>
    <p>
      This isn&rsquo;t maintenance. It&rsquo;s meditation. The ritual is how you stay connected
      to the machine between drives. It&rsquo;s the quiet hours in the garage with the radio on,
      the door open, nowhere to be. Some people garden. You detail.
    </p>
    <p>
      The ritual is what separates someone who <em>has</em> an automobile
      from someone who <em>lives with</em> one.
    </p>

    <h2>10. The Tribe</h2>
    <p>
      Then you find the others. The forum where people argue about the correct tire pressure
      for a track day. The Sunday morning meet where a guy in a &euro;3,000 Miata parks next to
      a &euro;300,000 Ferrari and they talk for an hour. The WhatsApp group that lights up
      when someone spots a barn find.
    </p>
    <p>
      Automobile people recognize automobile people.
      The tribe doesn&rsquo;t care what you drive &mdash; it cares that you care.
    </p>

    <h2>11. The Story</h2>
    <p>
      Every automobile becomes a story. The road trip where the alternator died in the middle
      of nowhere. The first time you took your kid for a ride. The afternoon you spent
      in the garage just listening to the engine idle.
    </p>
    <p>You don&rsquo;t collect automobiles. You collect chapters.</p>

    <h2>12. The Confirmation</h2>
    <p>
      Years pass. The model you bought is now sought-after. The critics who dismissed it
      have come around. The automobile that was &ldquo;just&rdquo; a daily driver is now a modern classic.
      Or maybe it&rsquo;s simpler than that &mdash; you still smile every time you see it in the driveway.
    </p>
    <p>
      The confirmation isn&rsquo;t about the market validating your choice. It&rsquo;s about time
      proving your instinct right. That pull you felt at the beginning? It knew.
    </p>

    <div class="border-top-dashed margin-block-double"></div>

    <p>
      Not every automobile enthusiast stacks all twelve layers. Some live for the hunt
      and lose interest once they buy. Some skip the bet entirely &mdash; they don&rsquo;t care
      about value, just the drive. Some are all tribe, all story.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the magic is in the stack. The more layers you feel, the deeper the love.
      And that&rsquo;s why &ldquo;I love automobiles&rdquo; never quite covers it.
    </p>

    <h3>P.S. &mdash; The Letting Go</h3>
    <p>
      It doesn&rsquo;t belong in the stack. It comes after. Sometimes years after.
    </p>
    <p>
      You sell it. Maybe you need the money. Maybe you&rsquo;ve found the next one.
      Maybe life just moved on and the garage needs to become something else.
    </p>
    <p>
      The ad goes up. Strangers come look at it. They ask questions you already know
      the answers to. And when someone drives it away, you stand in the empty space
      where it used to be, and you realize something: you didn&rsquo;t know how much
      it mattered until it was gone.
    </p>
    <p>
      The letting go isn&rsquo;t a layer of pleasure.
      It&rsquo;s the proof that all the other layers were real.
    </p>
  </article>

  <section class="pad-double txt-align-center fill-amber-lightest">
    <p class="txt-medium margin-block-end-half">This is why we built Crooz.</p>
    <p class="txt-subtle margin-block-end">Your garage. Your stories. Your crew.</p>
    <%= link_to "Open your garage", root_path, class: "btn btn--link" %>
  </section>

  <footer class="pad txt-align-center txt-small fill-asphalt txt-dust">
    <p class="margin-none">Built by people who get it. 🚗</p>
  </footer>
</main>
